<h1>@HI{{no}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N1{{}} <strong>@HI{{no}}</strong> @N2{{}}
<li> @Splain{{}} <strong>@HI{{no}}</strong> ...
<li> @S{{}} <strong>@HI{{no}}</strong>.
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{no}}</strong> can be used between two nouns to:
<ul>
<li> indicate possession
<li> indicate position or location
<li> indicate that the first noun modifies the second in terms of position or location
<li> inicate that the two nouns are in apposition
</ul>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{no}}</strong> can be used in place of @HI{{ga}} to mark the subject in a
<a href="grammar-relative-clause.html">relative clause</a>.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{no}}</strong> can be to <a href="grammar-no-nominaliser.html">nominalise</a> verbs and adjectives:
<ul>
<li> as a simple nominaliser corresponding to "~ing" or "what"
<li> as a nominaliser before verbs of perception
</ul>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{no}}</strong> can be used as a sentence ending particle:
<ul>
<li> as a question marker in colloquial sentences
<li> to soften a sentence
<li> to indicate a mild command
</ul>
</p>

